<!-- 3.1.5 -->
<div class='toload definition'>
	<p><span class='envidentifier'>Definition 3.1.5</span>
	Let $\mathcal{A}\subseteq C_c(X)$ be a subset containing $\theta$. Denote $\sigma(\mathcal{A})=\left\{\sigma(f):f\in\mathcal{A}\right\}$. We say that $(X,\theta,\mathcal{A})$ (or simply $\mathcal{A}$) is
	<ol>
		<li>
			<em>weakly regular</em> if $\sigma(\mathcal{A})$ is a basis for the topology of $X$.
		</li>
		
		<li>
			<em>regular</em> if for every $x\in X$, every neighbourhood $U$ of $x$ and every $c\in H$ there is $f\in\mathcal{A}$ with $f(x)=c$ and $\supp(f)\subseteq U$.
		</li>
	</ol>
	</p>
</div>